==Additive bases==
A subset formula_30 with the property that formula_35 for a finite sum, is called an additive basis, and the least number of summands required is called the &quot;degree&quot; (sometimes &quot;order&quot;) of the basis. Thus, the last theorem states that any set with positive Schnirelmann density is an additive basis. In this terminology, the set of squares formula_6 is an additive basis of degree 4. (About an open problem for additive bases, see Erdős–Turán conjecture on additive bases.)

==Mann&#x27;s theorem==
Historically the theorems above were pointers to the following result, at one time known as the formula_37 hypothesis. It was used by Edmund Landau and was finally proved by Henry Mann in 1942.
Theorem. Let formula_16 and formula_17 be subsets of formula_15. In case that formula_41, we still have
formula_42

An analogue of this theorem for lower asymptotic density was obtained by Kneser. At a later date, E. Artin and P. Scherk simplified the proof of Mann&#x27;s theorem.

==Waring&#x27;s problem==
Let formula_43 and formula_44 be natural numbers. Let formula_45. Define formula_46 to be the number of non-negative integral solutions to the equation

:formula_47

and formula_48 to be the number of non-negative integral solutions to the inequality

